canonical:
  title: 元敬王后上諡玉冊文
  author: 尹淮
  language: lzh
  text: 毓德儷尊徽音夙著易名定謚哀懇實深祗率舊章載揚顯冊恭惟齋莊貞靜淵懿溫恭儆戒無違克合在中之吉柔嘉維則式推逮下之仁謂享遐齡益膺純嘏何神機之厭世奄仙御之乘雲奉養未終慨音容之永閟追攀莫及撫胸臆以增悲聿申歸美之情敢擧彌文之典謹擧冊上尊謚曰云云仰惟冲鑑庶允休稱
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 元敬王后上諡玉冊文
  author: 尹淮
  language: lzh
  text: 毓德儷尊。徽音夙著。易名定謚。哀懇實深。祗率舊章。載揚顯冊。恭惟齋莊貞靜。淵懿溫恭。儆戒無違。克合在中之吉。柔嘉維則。式推逮下之仁。謂享遐齡。益膺純嘏。何神機之厭世。奄仙御之乘雲。奉養未終。慨音容之永閟。追攀莫及。撫胸臆以增悲。聿申歸美之情。敢擧彌文之典。謹擧冊上尊謚曰云云。仰惟冲鑑。庶允休稱。
korean:
  title: 원경왕후 상시 옥책문
  author: 윤회
  language: kor
  text: 덕을 길러 지존의 배필이 되시매 아름다운 명성이 일찍 드러나셨으며, 이름을 고쳐 시호를 정하매 슬픈 마음이 실로 깊습니다. 공손하게 옛법에 따라서 밝은 옥책을 들추옵니다.공손히 생각하옵건대, 정제하고 씩씩하고 정숙하고 고요하시며, 깊고 아름답고 온순하고 공손하셨습니다. 조심하여 지아비에게 어김이 없으시어 능히 곤괘(坤卦)와 부합되셨고, 유순하고 아름다움이 법이 되어 아랫사람에 미치는 사랑을 잘 넓히셨습니다. 오래도록 수를 누리시와 더욱 순수한 복을 받으시리라 여겼더니, 어찌하여 세상을 싫어하시와 문득 신선의 행차로 구름을 타시옵는지요. 봉양함을 마치지 못하였기에 음성과 형용의 길이 감춰짐이 개탄스럽고, 부여잡아도 미칠 수 없으며 가슴을 두드리면서 더욱 슬퍼하옵니다.이에 드디어 귀미(歸美)의 정성을 펴서, 감히 빛나는 예전을 거행하옵니다. 삼가 책을 받들어 존시를 올리오니, 오직 밝게 굽어보시와, 아름다운 칭호를 받으시옵소서.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0320_010_0200&viewSync=OT
  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Eulogy and Jade Inscription for the Consort of King Wongyeong
  author: Yun Hoe
  language: eng
  text: |-
    She cultivated virtue to stand as consort to the throne,
    her luminous name resplendent from the start.
    In fixed epitaph and proper station,
    our grief runs deep and true.
    Following ancient rite with reverent heart,
    we unfold this radiant jade proclamation.

    Consider her restraint and steadfast grace,
    her quiet dignity and gentle bearing—
    deep in wisdom, warm in deference.
    Undeviating in her dutiful way,
    she embodied the auspicious nature of Earth itself.
    Soft and virtuous, she became the measure
    by which compassion flows to all below.

    We thought her years would stretch long,
    blessed abundantly with perfect fortune.
    Yet how swiftly Heaven turned its face away—
    she departed on celestial clouds,
    becoming one with the immortals.

    The care we rendered was left unfinished;
    her voice and countenance are sealed from us forever.
    Though we reach and cannot grasp her,
    we beat our breasts in deepening sorrow.

    Now we offer this testament of her virtue,
    daring to perform this solemn rite.
    With reverent hands we present this jade inscription,
    beseeching your bright discernment
    to honor her with worthy name eternal.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Jade Inscription' (옥책) refers to a formal document inscribed on jade used in royal ceremonies to confer posthumous titles and honors.
    - The reference to 'the auspicious nature of Earth itself' alludes to the Kun hexagram (坤卦), symbol of receptivity and the feminine principle in the I Ching.
    - This work is a 'Guishu wen' (歸美文), a ceremonial document that consecrates virtue and beauty back to the deceased through formal recognition.
